---
import CaseStudyLayout from '../../layouts/CaseStudyLayout.astro';

const data = {
  metaTitle: "Property Management Platform | All Webbed Labs Case Study",
  metaDescription: "How a Sydney property management company managing 400 properties consolidated four software tools into one platform, cutting maintenance response time from 4.2 hours to 47 minutes and lifting staff capacity by 35%.",

  industry: "Real Estate",
  tags: ["Property Management", "Maintenance Workflow", "Tenant App", "Owner Portal", "Trust Accounting"],

  title: "Property Management Platform",
  summary: "A Sydney residential property management company managing 400 properties across inner and middle Sydney replaced four separate software tools and a fragmented manual workflow with an integrated platform, cutting average maintenance response time from 4.2 hours to 47 minutes and enabling each property manager to handle 35% more properties.",

  heroImageDescription: "Property manager reviewing a maintenance request dashboard on a desktop monitor in a modern real estate office, with tenant and owner communication threads visible on screen",

  // CASE_STUDY_PLACEHOLDER — replace with real client details when approved
  clientOverview: "Harbour & Hills Property is a Sydney-based residential property management agency managing 400 properties across the inner suburbs and middle ring — predominantly apartments in Newtown, Surry Hills, Glebe, and Leichhardt, and houses in the inner west. With 12 staff managing the portfolio, the company has built a reputation for responsive communication but was facing real operational pressure as the portfolio grew beyond what their existing systems could handle without proportionate headcount increases.",
  clientSize: "12 staff · 400 properties under management",
  clientLocation: "Sydney, NSW",

  pullQuote: "We were spending so much time just keeping the different systems talking to each other — manually copying information from one place to another — that we weren't actually managing properties, we were managing software. Now that the information lives in one place, the actual job of property management is what we do.",
  pullQuoteAuthor: "Principal",
  pullQuoteRole: "Harbour & Hills Property",

  challenge: [
    "Harbour & Hills was operating across four separate software platforms that didn't integrate with each other. PropertyMe handled the core property and tenancy records. A separate maintenance management system (a product intended for facilities management rather than residential PM) handled maintenance requests. Owner communications happened via email, with statements prepared manually in Microsoft Word. Trust accounting reconciliation was done in a combination of PropertyMe's basic reporting and Excel, with the final reconciliation requiring manual comparison between PropertyMe's trust ledger and Xero.",
    "The maintenance workflow was the most acute problem. When a tenant reported a maintenance issue — typically by phone or email to the office — a staff member would enter the request into the maintenance system, then separately email a tradesperson, then follow up the tradesperson by phone, then update the maintenance system with the tradesperson's response, then email or call the tenant with an update, then notify the owner if the cost exceeded the agency's authority limit, wait for owner approval, confirm back to the tradesperson, and then close the job once the work was done and invoiced. Every maintenance job involved six to eight manual touchpoints across three different systems. At 400 properties generating an average of 2.3 maintenance requests per property per year, this represented a significant daily administrative load.",
    "The data quality problems that resulted from operating four systems were significant. A tenant's phone number updated in PropertyMe might not be reflected in the maintenance system for days. An owner's bank account change entered in the trust accounting spreadsheet needed to be manually replicated in Xero. Maintenance history for a property existed in one system, financial history in another, and owner communication history in email threads that were not searchable by property. When a new property manager joined the team and took over a portfolio, assembling the context for each property required pulling information from three or four places and hoping it was consistent.",
    "Owner statements were prepared monthly by each property manager using a Word template they filled in manually from PropertyMe's transaction reports. The process took each PM approximately 15 to 20 minutes per statement, adding up to roughly three hours per week across the portfolio. The statements were attached to emails and sent individually. Any owner who called with a query about their statement required the PM to look up the PropertyMe report again and cross-reference it with the email they'd sent — a conversation that could become awkward when the PM was looking at the same raw data the owner was querying and couldn't immediately explain a specific line item.",
    "Tenant onboarding was paper-based. Rental applications were submitted as PDF forms attached to emails, printed, manually reviewed, and physically filed. Reference checks were conducted by phone, with the outcome noted in a field in PropertyMe. Routine inspection scheduling was managed through a combination of a wall planner and individual PM calendars, with no systematic tracking of when each property was due for inspection, how many inspections had been completed in the current tenancy period, or whether inspection reports had been sent to owners within the required timeframe under the NSW Residential Tenancies Act 2010.",
    "Under the Residential Tenancies Act 2010 (NSW) and the associated Property and Stock Agents Act 2002, property managers have specific obligations around routine inspection frequency, maintenance response documentation, and trust accounting. The company's principal was increasingly concerned that the manual processes left them exposed — not through any deliberate non-compliance, but because the documentation that would demonstrate compliance was scattered across multiple systems and email inboxes rather than systematically maintained."
  ],

  whyUs: [
    "Harbour & Hills' principal had spent considerable time researching available property management platforms. The company had trialled two additional SaaS products in the previous 18 months, neither of which had solved the core problem. The fundamental issue was that no existing platform handled the combination of residential property management depth (PropertyMe does this well) with the maintenance workflow automation, owner portal, and tenant app functionality they needed in a single integrated system. The options were either to add more best-of-breed point solutions and accept the integration problem, or to build something integrated.",
    "The recommendation to explore a custom build came from the company's accountant, who had seen another professional services client benefit from replacing a fragmented software stack with an integrated custom platform. The accountant's framing was financial: the cost of maintaining four software subscriptions, the cost of the staff time consumed by manual data re-entry between systems, and the cost of the errors that resulted from that re-entry, together approached the cost of a custom build within two to three years. Presented this way, the investment case was straightforward.",
    "We were engaged after a single meeting in which we mapped the four existing systems against a proposed integrated data model and demonstrated that all the key data relationships could be handled in a single PostgreSQL schema. That technical demonstration gave the principal confidence that we understood the domain — that we knew what a trust ledger was, how periodic payments worked, what the NSW inspection frequency requirements were, and how maintenance history related to owner liability. Domain knowledge matters in property management software; generic software development skills are not sufficient."
  ],

  approach: [
    "The discovery phase required understanding three distinct user groups with different needs: property managers (who needed a fast, keyboard-efficient desktop experience for day-to-day portfolio management), tenants (who needed a simple mobile experience to submit maintenance requests and communicate with their PM), and owners (who needed visibility of their investment performance without being overwhelmed by operational detail). We built separate user journey maps for each group and validated them through structured interviews — four property managers, eight tenants recruited through the agency, and five owners.",
    "The tenant interviews were particularly illuminating. The agency had assumed tenants primarily wanted to use an app to submit maintenance requests. The interviews revealed that what tenants wanted most was visibility — knowing that their request had been received, that a tradesperson had been engaged, and when the work would be done. The submission mechanism was secondary to the status transparency. This reframing changed the design priority for the tenant app: the most important screen wasn't the submission form but the maintenance tracker that showed current status, expected completion, and who to contact with questions.",
    "The trust accounting integration was the most technically complex element of the project. NSW trust accounting for property management is governed by specific requirements under the Property and Stock Agents Regulation 2022, including how trust funds must be held, reconciled, and audited. We engaged a property management industry consultant for two half-day sessions to map the complete trust accounting data model and identify the reconciliation requirements. This investment in domain expertise prevented us from designing a system that was functionally plausible but procedurally non-compliant with the audit requirements that all licensed NSW real estate agencies face.",
    "We made an early decision to use Flutter for both the tenant app and the owner app. The tenant demographic was young and smartphone-first; the owner demographic was more varied and included older investors who used iPads rather than Android phones. Flutter's cross-platform capability was the practical choice. The office staff dashboard was built in React, which gave us the dense, data-rich interface appropriate for professional desktop use — keyboard shortcuts, tabbed navigation, right-click context menus — that would have felt out of place in a mobile app context."
  ],

  solution: [
    "The platform's core is a unified data model in PostgreSQL that holds every entity in a single consistent schema: properties, tenancies, tenants, owners, maintenance jobs, inspection records, financial transactions, and documents. There is no synchronisation required between systems because there is only one system. When a tenant's contact details change, every view in the platform reflects that change immediately — the PM's dashboard, the maintenance job record, the owner's portal, and the document history.",
    "The maintenance workflow is fully automated through the new platform. When a tenant submits a request through the app or portal, the system creates a maintenance job record, notifies the assigned property manager, and (for categories below the property's pre-approved spend authority) automatically sends an SMS and email to the relevant preferred tradesperson. The tradesperson receives a structured job brief with the property address, access notes, and contact details. When they confirm, the system notifies the tenant with the appointment time. Job completion triggers a completion photo requirement from the tradesperson, an owner notification, and a satisfaction prompt to the tenant. The PM is involved only when the job requires owner approval for cost, when the job is complex, or when the tenant or tradesperson flags an issue.",
    "The owner portal, accessible via web browser and the Flutter owner app, shows each owner their property's occupancy status, upcoming lease events (renewal date, inspection schedule), maintenance job history and current status, and a financial dashboard with rental income, expenses, and net position by month. Monthly statements are generated automatically and are available in the portal the moment the period closes — owners receive a notification and can review the statement directly in the app without waiting for an emailed PDF. The statement format was designed in close consultation with the company's accountant to ensure the line item descriptions, trust accounting presentation, and tax-relevant categorisation were correct.",
    "Tenant onboarding was rebuilt from scratch. Prospective tenants complete a digital application directly in the platform, with identity verification handled through an integration with the TICA (Tenancy Information Centre Australasia) database and a reference submission workflow that sends automated emails to nominated referees with structured questionnaires rather than relying on a PM phone call. Applications go through an approval workflow that documents the decision and the basis for it — important for compliance with NSW anti-discrimination requirements that apply to tenancy decisions.",
    "Routine inspections are now scheduled by the system based on tenancy start dates and NSW Residential Tenancies Act requirements — four inspections in the first 12 months, then as specified in the tenancy agreement within the legislative limits. PMs receive a weekly inspection schedule with all properties due in the coming fortnight. Inspection reports are completed on the PM's phone using a structured template with mandatory photo sections for key areas. Completed reports are automatically sent to the owner and stored against the property record, with the send timestamp forming part of the compliance audit trail."
  ],

  techStack: [
    { name: "React", reason: "Staff dashboard — complex multi-property data views, keyboard-first navigation, dense professional interface" },
    { name: "Flutter", reason: "Tenant and owner mobile apps — single codebase covering iOS and Android for diverse user demographics" },
    { name: "Node.js", reason: "REST API backend with event-driven maintenance workflow automation" },
    { name: "PostgreSQL", reason: "Unified data model replacing four separate systems — all relationships in one schema" },
    { name: "Xero Integration", reason: "Trust accounting reconciliation and owner disbursement — automated rather than manually re-entered" },
    { name: "AWS S3", reason: "Document storage for inspection reports, tenancy agreements, maintenance photos, and owner statements" },
    { name: "Push Notifications", reason: "Tenant maintenance updates, owner approval requests, PM task alerts — via FCM and APNs" },
    { name: "Twilio SMS", reason: "Tradesperson job notifications and tenant appointment confirmations via SMS for maximum reach" }
  ],

  implementation: [
    "Data migration from four existing systems was the most complex implementation challenge. PropertyMe had an export capability for property and tenancy records that produced reasonably clean CSV files. The maintenance system's export was poorly structured — a flat file that lost the relationship between parent work orders and sub-tasks. We spent three weeks writing and testing migration scripts, and ran a parallel period where both the old systems and the new platform received all data for two weeks, allowing the PMs to spot discrepancies between what they expected to see and what appeared in the new system.",
    "The 400-property migration was completed over a single weekend, with two staff from both sides working through a detailed runbook. We had prepared rollback procedures in case the migration encountered unexpected data quality issues — in practice, we needed them for 23 properties where historical maintenance records had relationship inconsistencies in the source data. Those 23 were migrated manually over the following Monday and Tuesday. The principal confirmed zero data loss on the post-migration audit.",
    "Staff training was structured around user roles. Property managers received a full-day workshop covering the dashboard, maintenance workflow, inspection module, and owner communication features. The bookkeeper received a separate half-day session focused entirely on the trust accounting reconciliation and Xero integration. The training approach emphasised doing over explaining — every staff member completed a full simulated workflow during the session using a test environment populated with synthetic data.",
    "Tenant and owner onboarding was rolled out in cohorts to avoid overwhelming the support capacity. The first 80 tenants and 60 owners were invited to the platform over the first four weeks. The company's communications to these cohorts were carefully worded — framing the app as a service improvement rather than a cost-cutting exercise, and emphasising the maintenance tracking visibility as the primary benefit for tenants. App adoption reached 71% of tenants within six weeks and 84% within three months; the remaining 16% were long-standing tenants who preferred phone contact and were supported through the PM interface without requiring app use."
  ],

  lessonsLearned: [
    "The decision to build both a tenant app and an owner app as native-quality Flutter applications, rather than mobile web portals, was the right call but added significant development time and testing complexity. We encountered several platform-specific behaviours in the Flutter iOS build — particularly around push notification permission handling — that required fixes specific to one platform without breaking the other. Future projects of this scope should budget explicitly for cross-platform divergence testing, not assume the Flutter codebase will behave identically on both platforms in all scenarios.",
    "The trust accounting integration with Xero took longer than projected because the mapping between property management trust accounting concepts and Xero's general ledger model is non-trivial. Xero doesn't have a native trust account concept; modelling trust liabilities and disbursements correctly in Xero's chart of accounts required the involvement of the accountant throughout the integration phase, not just at the beginning. For future projects involving trust accounting, we'll require an accountant to be part of the project team from discovery through to go-live acceptance testing.",
    "The maintenance tradesperson onboarding created a dynamic we hadn't fully anticipated: the tradespeople who had worked with Harbour & Hills for years had well-established phone relationships with specific PMs, and some of them initially resisted the SMS-based job notification system because they preferred a call from 'someone they knew.' This wasn't a technical problem — it was a change management problem. The principal addressed it directly by calling each of the six most important tradespeople personally to explain the change and ask for their patience during the transition period. All six are now fully operating through the platform."
  ],

  whatCameNext: [
    "Three months after go-live, the principal used the portfolio performance data now available in the platform to conduct a review of the agency's fee structure. With the cost per property now visible — maintenance overhead, inspection time, owner communication volume — the company identified seven properties where the management fees were below the cost of service, and approached those owners for fee adjustments. Two owners declined and moved to another agency; five accepted. The data that made this conversation possible didn't exist before the platform.",
    "The company has since used the increased per-PM capacity — from 33 to 45 properties per manager — to grow the portfolio by 60 properties without adding headcount. The additional revenue from those 60 properties, against a largely fixed cost base, directly improved the business's profitability. The principal has described this as the clearest return on the platform investment.",
    "Work is currently underway on a lease renewal module that automates the negotiation and documentation of residential lease renewals under NSW Residential Tenancies Act requirements, including the prescribed notice periods and the documentation of rent increase notices in compliance with the Act's rent increase frequency restrictions."
  ],

  resultsNarrative: "After the first six months on the platform, average maintenance response time dropped from 4.2 hours to 47 minutes, owner statement preparation time fell from three hours per week to 20 minutes, tenant satisfaction scores for maintenance handling improved from 2.9 out of 5 to 4.6, and each property manager's capacity increased from 33 to 45 properties — a 35% gain that enabled portfolio growth without new headcount. All 400 properties were migrated with zero data loss.",

  metrics: [
    { value: "47 min", label: "Average maintenance response time", context: "Down from 4.2 hours — fully automated workflow" },
    { value: "20 min", label: "Weekly owner statement prep", context: "Down from 3 hours — automated generation and delivery" },
    { value: "4.6/5", label: "Tenant maintenance satisfaction", context: "Up from 2.9 — driven by status transparency in tenant app" },
    { value: "35%", label: "Increase in PM handling capacity", context: "From 33 to 45 properties per manager" },
    { value: "400", label: "Properties migrated", context: "Zero data loss across four source systems" },
    { value: "84%", label: "Tenant app adoption", context: "Reached within 3 months of launch" }
  ],

  relatedCaseStudies: [
    {
      title: "Commercial Property Listing & CRM",
      href: "/case-studies/commercial-property-listing-crm",
      industry: "Real Estate",
      summary: "A Melbourne commercial real estate agency replaced a Dropbox spreadsheet with a purpose-built listing and CRM platform, lifting agent pipeline visibility and cutting lead response time from 48 hours to under 2 hours."
    },
    {
      title: "Rental Application & Background Check Platform",
      href: "/case-studies/rental-application-background-check",
      industry: "Real Estate",
      summary: "A Perth residential property manager processing 80–120 applications per month cut processing time from 5 days to same-day for 80% of applications with automated ID verification and tenancy database checks."
    },
    {
      title: "Quoting & Estimating Tool",
      href: "/case-studies/quoting-estimating-tool",
      industry: "Construction & Trades",
      summary: "An Adelaide custom home builder cut quote preparation from 3 days to 4 hours with a client portal, live material price feeds, and Xero integration."
    }
  ],

  relatedServices: [
    { title: "Custom Software Development", href: "/services/custom-app-development" },
    { title: "Mobile App Development", href: "/services/flutter-development" },
    { title: "Xero Integration", href: "/services/api-development" },
    { title: "Client Portal Development", href: "/services/custom-app-development" }
  ]
};
